Political Process and Resource Mobilization theories

Resource Mobilization

RMT: Basic Assumptions

Key citation: McCarthy, J. D., & Zald, M. N. (1977). Resource mobilization and social movements: A partial theory. American journal of sociology, 82(6), 1212-1241.

  1. âStrainâ alone is not sufficient because protest requires resources.

  2. Powerless groups lack access to these resources, so external actors have to supply them.

  3. Mobilization resources are finite, so activists form organizations to compete for them.

ââ¦there is always enough discontent in any society to supply the grass-roots support for a movement if the movement is effectively organized and has at its disposal the power and resources of some established elite groupâ - Ralph Turner and Lewis Killian (1972)

RMT: Key Actors

Social Movement

A set of opinions or preferences that favor changing society.

Social Movement Organizations (SMO)

Formal organizations aligned with an SM

Social Movement Industries (SMI)

The set of SMOs organized around an issue.

RMT: Mobilized groups

Movements need people, but who they mobilize is drives organizational behavior.

  • level of involvement
  • size/access to resources
  • relationship to the goals of the movement

Resource Mobilization and Civil Rights

  • Resource Mobilization Theorists offer a compelling explanation for the Civil Rights era and the explosion of movement activity after WWII
    • Economic changes: middle class with free time and discretionary income
    • Changes among elites: institutional support for activists from unions, political parties, and churches
    • Demographic shifts: growing college-educated workforce and lots of young people

From the perspective of resource mobilization theory, the best way to understand the civil rights movement is to understand the relationships between the organizations that made up its primary planners.

SMOs in this space differed in terms of their tactics, bases of support, and relationship with public.

External Support for Civil Rights SMOs

The history of the civil rights movement offers some support for this way of looking at the development of movements. The era saw money pour in to civil rights organizations from both elite grant-making institutions and from the general public - money that was essential to making ambitious and carefully orchestrated events like the March on Washington possible.

Critiques

Critiques: do powerless groups lack leverage?

  • Some tools are available to resource-poor groups without external support:

    • Labor strikes
    • Sit-ins, boycotts and other forms of disruption
    • Riots and the threat of violence

Piven and Cloward are especially relevant here: their model of âPoor Peopleâs Movementsâ emphasizes the role of creating âcrisesâ in the advancement of the interests of the working class. Elites, who are viewed as typically hostile to new challengers, only respond to the demands of excluded groups when these crises force them to do so (the more cynical interpretation of new deal policies and the expansion of the American welfare state is that it was a way of demobilizing support for deeper structural changes)

Truly revolutionary demands essentially never get sustained elite support. This tends to go towards the most moderate, institutionalist groups.

Critiques: the role of grievance

  • Grievance is alone is not enough, but neither are grievances + resources.

  • Many grievances are de-politicized, viewed as just or the result of personal failures, or viewed as insurmountable through collective action.

Critiques: the role of elites and organizations

  • Do professional groups do most of the heavy lifting for movements?

  • Is elite/institutional support an unalloyed good? What are the downsides?

  • What are the strategic goals of elites/institutional supporters?

It is not possible to compel concessions from elites that can be used as resources to sustain oppositional organizations over timeâ¦ Organizations endure, in short, by abandoning their oppositional politics.

Piven, Frances Fox, and Richard Cloward. Poor peopleâs movements: Why they succeed, how they fail. Vintage, 1978.

Critiques: Elite support and moderation

Elite supporters channel insurgents through âproperâ political channels where the disparity between the haves and the have nots is at its worst. Elite support is partly a means of social control.

In the CRM, this meant elite funding inevitably went towards the most institutionalized SMOs: the NAACP, LDF, and Urban League took the largest share of institutional funding, whereas more radical direct-action groups received far less support.

Moreover, the external support that went to groups like CORE and SNCC came with considerable strings attached, and critics of RMT argue that this was a response to their emergence as important players rather than the cause of that change (Radical Flank Effects)

Political Process Model

3 key factors

Social strain matters, but only indirectly through the way it reshapes existing power structures and creates space for new challengers. I.e. through changes in the political opportunity structure

Opportunity Structures are these system-level features that make the political sphere more or less open. Includes things like: - elite support/receptiveness/vulnerability of established opposition - features of the constitutional order (electoral system, veto players etc.) - Organizational Readiness: - membership patterns and the feasibility of bloc recruitment - structure of solidary incentives (non-material selective incentives that might be available.) - dense communication networks - leaders

Cognitive Liberation: - social re-construction of grievances as political and amenable to collective action - actors must recognize a problem, view it as wrong, and then choose to politicize it

Civil Rights: Socioeconomic processes

  • Post-Reconstruction period (1877 - 1920s): low point for civil rights in the U.S.

  • Increasing black electoral power following WWI (but continued segregation in the south)

  • Post WWII: emerging black middle class, weakening of the north-south elite party alliance, sympathetic Supreme Court

Reconstruction ends in 1877 following the contested election of Rutherford B. Hayes. Explicitly or implicitly: Republicans all but abandoned efforts to enfranchise blacks in the south or police racial violence. Supreme Court neutered the reconstruction amendments and jim crow laws cemented formal second class status for southern blacks

Booker T. Washington in 1913: âhad never seen the colored people so discouraged and bitter as they are at the present time.â

Labor shortages in the north during WWI drive a wave of black migration to urban centers above the Mason-Dixon, which changes the political calculus because black people could vote in the north, so they had to be taken seriously as a constituency. Urban churches become key centers of power (rural churches were too dispersed to exert much political influence). Black colleges have a similar trajectory.

Liberalization after WWII: black movement into the electorate accelerates, and black voters are a key constituency (albeit poorly served) in the Roosevelt years. FDR himself is personally more sympathetic to racial equality than Wilson (the last Dem to occupy the White House): symbolic gestures like dining with a black musician at the White House or issuing frank condemnations of lynchings represented clear - but New Deal programs still generally excluded blacks.

Pro Civil Rights majority on the Supreme Court creates lots of opportunities for new legal challenges (NAACP legal defense fund starts around this era)

Civil Rights: Political Opportunity Structures in 1960s

  • Partisan competition: black voters became a key swing constituency

  • Increased public attention/sympathy for civil rights causes

  • Sense among elites that segregation undermines U.S. global reputation; concerns about the effect of (esp.Â televised) violence on public opinion

Civil Rights: elites and demobilization

  • Indigenous collective action gives way to professional groups.

  • King assassinated in 1968, leading to decline of SCLC.

  • Funding declines precipitously in late 1960s

  • Party incentives around black voters see a dramatic shift in 1968 and beyond.
